So here's a really cool example of us doing this really successfully. So imagine that

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:45.000
you want to take a measurement from the bottom of the plant to the first leaf on the shoot.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:49.000
And that that process, I mean, typically, again, the default is that there's not instrumentation

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:54.000
out there. So someone is physically holding that plant and physically taking a measurement

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:59.000
device to it. And then they maybe, like, type it down or something like that. So something

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.000
we've done that's been really successful is, okay, cool, somebody wants to move that into

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:09.000
digital space. So we're going to take a picture of the plant. And then we get the person to

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:14.000
take that measurement from the picture. And what that does is it means you have to align

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:19.000
the resolution necessary for that person to then do the task has to be in the picture

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:24.000
in order for them to execute on that successfully. And so that can be a good paradigm to do that.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:31.000
And I think there's similar parallels in other applications as well.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:36.000
So calibration. Calibration is also really critical. So let's talk about that quickly.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:41.000
There's tons and tons of great content in the world about this. But you want to quantify

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:47.000
your measurement system error. Every measurement system has error. You have no clue. Like,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:53.000
if you wanted to characterize the room temperatures, the temperatures in this room, whatever device

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
you're going to use is going to have error. You need to understand what that is and what

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:04.000
the caveats are. I would consider using a derived metric. So, yeah, again, let's take

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:08.000
the temperature in this room. It has some set point, right? There's a thermostat here

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
somewhere that's trying to achieve a specific temperature. If you wanted to have an alert

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:20.000
be thrown on the HVAC system performing out of spec, don't set that limit on the actual

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:27.000
temperature. Set it as a margin on the set point. So, again, there's lots and lots of

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:32.000
great content in the world about that. And then consider having a standard data model

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:39.000
for your data. If you work with a lot of temperature data, you might want to have your own standard

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:46.000
system or structure for that data so that different instrumentation approaches you take,

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:52.000
different suppliers, you can merge all of that stuff and plug it into a constant approach,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:59.000
which you then can work on sort of agnostic of how you got that data to begin with.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:04.000
And if you do all these things, I think there's an opportunity to create a virtuous cycle,

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:09.000
right, where you're then collecting good data in the meat space. You're able to put it into

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:14.000
a database that you didn't create. And then you import that stuff. You go through your

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:19.000
data science workflow. You build understanding. And then that has the ability to feed back

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:30.000
into additional instrumentation and changes that might be made out in the real world.

